text.0:
A post on Facebook promoting the use of alternative medicine as a treatment for gunshot wounds is MISLEADING.

:magnifying_glass_tilted_right: Using coconut water in this way is not backed by science: https://t.co/z1plfNhOZH
text.1:
An image posted with a claim that the leader of Uganda's National Unity Platform party, Bobi Wine, and his supporters rioted is :cross_mark: FALSE.

:magnifying_glass_tilted_right: The image was taken in April 2011 during Walk-to-Work protests in response to high living costs: https://t.co/uSQgoOn7Pq
text.2:
An article claiming that Kenya's energy regulator has given the country's power distributor the go-ahead to implement a 20% electricity price hike is :cross_mark: FALSE.

:magnifying_glass_tilted_right: The regulator denies that it has approved a request to increase the price of electricity: https://t.co/VRX5XR17ZF
text.3:
:police_car_light: HOAX: A screenshot from a Twitter account using the name and image of Kenya’s President claiming he has asked the US not to interfere in Tanzania’s democratic process is fake.

:magnifying_glass_tilted_right: President Kenyatta does not have a Twitter account: https://t.co/qO4f01VR62
text.4:
A video posted on Twitter claiming to show a robbery in Nairobi is :cross_mark: FALSE.

:magnifying_glass_tilted_right: The incident took place in Johannesburg in December 2017: https://t.co/LSHnrCemx1
text.5:
A tweet from the account of Boni Khalwale, the former senator of Kenya's Kakamega County, claiming to show the Deputy President's motorcade in Nairobi is PARTLY FALSE.

:automobile: The image of the motorcade is from 2018 and not from the date indicated in the post: https://t.co/aFrRhJ5WDc
